---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Cassandra Compaction Strategies"
  description="Interactive visualization of Cassandra's LSM-Tree compaction strategies: Size-Tiered (STCS), Leveled (LCS), and Time-Window (TWCS)"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: "Home", href: "/" },
    { label: "Cassandra", href: "/cassandra/" },
    { label: "Compaction Strategies", href: "/cassandra/compaction/" }
  ]}
>
<div class="viz-container">
  <header class="viz-header">
    <h1>🗜️ Cassandra Compaction Strategies</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">How Cassandra Merges SSTables to Keep Reads Fast</p>
  </header>

  <!-- Overview -->
  <section class="overview-section">
    <div class="overview-card">
      <p>
        Cassandra uses an <strong>LSM-Tree</strong> (Log-Structured Merge Tree) storage engine.
        Writes go to an in-memory <em>MemTable</em>, which flushes to immutable on-disk <em>SSTables</em>.
        Over time, SSTables accumulate — reads must check multiple files, increasing <strong>read amplification</strong>.
        <strong>Compaction</strong> merges SSTables, removes tombstones, and consolidates data to keep reads efficient.
        Cassandra offers three main strategies: <em>Size-Tiered (STCS)</em>, <em>Leveled (LCS)</em>, and <em>Time-Window (TWCS)</em>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- LSM-Tree Write Flow -->
  <section class="flow-section">
    <h2>📝 LSM-Tree Write Flow</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">Watch writes flow through the LSM-Tree: MemTable fills up, flushes to disk as an immutable SSTable, and SSTables pile up over time.</p>

    <div class="flow-controls">
      <button id="writeBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">✍ Write Data</button>
      <button id="flushBtn" class="action-btn step-btn" disabled>💾 Flush to Disk</button>
      <button id="autoWriteBtn" class="action-btn auto-btn">⚡ Auto-Play</button>
      <button id="resetLsmBtn" class="action-btn reset-btn">🔄 Reset</button>
    </div>

    <div class="flow-status" id="lsmStatus">
      <span class="status-badge idle" id="lsmBadge">Ready</span>
      <span class="status-text" id="lsmStatusText">Click "Write Data" to add entries to the MemTable</span>
    </div>

    <div class="topology-container">
      <canvas id="lsmCanvas" width="820" height="400"></canvas>
    </div>

    <div class="failover-timeline" id="lsmTimeline"></div>
  </section>

  <!-- LSM-Tree Explainer -->
  <section class="explain-section">
    <div class="explain-grid">
      <div class="explain-card">
        <h3>📥 Write Path</h3>
        <p>
          Every write goes to the <strong>commit log</strong> (for durability) and then to the
          <em>MemTable</em> (in-memory sorted structure). When the MemTable reaches its threshold,
          it's flushed to disk as an <strong>immutable SSTable</strong>. Writes are always sequential
          — no random I/O — making Cassandra extremely <em>write-optimized</em>.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="explain-card">
        <h3>📖 Read Path</h3>
        <p>
          Reads check the <strong>MemTable first</strong>, then SSTables from newest to oldest.
          <em>Bloom filters</em> skip SSTables that definitely don't contain the key. Without compaction,
          reads degrade as SSTables accumulate — this is <strong>read amplification</strong>.
          Compaction reduces the number of SSTables a read must check.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Size-Tiered Compaction (STCS) -->
  <section class="flow-section">
    <h2>📦 Size-Tiered Compaction (STCS)</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">The default strategy. SSTables of similar size are grouped and merged. Watch SSTables accumulate and trigger compaction when enough similar-sized tables exist.</p>

    <div class="flow-controls">
      <button id="stcsAddBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">➕ Add SSTable</button>
      <button id="stcsCompactBtn" class="action-btn step-btn" disabled>🗜️ Compact</button>
      <button id="stcsAutoBtn" class="action-btn auto-btn">⚡ Auto-Play</button>
      <button id="stcsResetBtn" class="action-btn reset-btn">🔄 Reset</button>
    </div>

    <div class="flow-status" id="stcsStatus">
      <span class="status-badge idle" id="stcsBadge">Ready</span>
      <span class="status-text" id="stcsStatusText">Add SSTables to see size-tiered compaction in action</span>
    </div>

    <div class="topology-container">
      <canvas id="stcsCanvas" width="820" height="350"></canvas>
    </div>

    <div class="failover-timeline" id="stcsTimeline"></div>
  </section>

  <!-- STCS Explainer -->
  <section class="explain-section">
    <div class="explain-card highlight-card">
      <h3>💡 How STCS Works</h3>
      <p>
        SSTables are grouped into <strong>buckets by size</strong>. When a bucket has
        <em>min_threshold</em> (default 4) SSTables of similar size, they're merged into
        one larger SSTable. This new SSTable may then join a higher-size bucket.
        <strong>Pros:</strong> excellent write throughput, simple logic.
        <strong>Cons:</strong> temporary <em>2× space amplification</em> during compaction
        (old + new SSTables coexist), and SSTables can grow very large.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Leveled Compaction (LCS) -->
  <section class="flow-section">
    <h2>📊 Leveled Compaction (LCS)</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">SSTables are organized into levels. Each level is 10× bigger than the previous. No overlapping key ranges within a level (except L0). Watch data promote through levels.</p>

    <div class="flow-controls">
      <button id="lcsAddBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">➕ Add to L0</button>
      <button id="lcsCompactBtn" class="action-btn step-btn" disabled>⬆️ Promote</button>
      <button id="lcsAutoBtn" class="action-btn auto-btn">⚡ Auto-Play</button>
      <button id="lcsResetBtn" class="action-btn reset-btn">🔄 Reset</button>
    </div>

    <div class="flow-status" id="lcsStatus">
      <span class="status-badge idle" id="lcsBadge">Ready</span>
      <span class="status-text" id="lcsStatusText">Add SSTables to L0 and watch them promote through levels</span>
    </div>

    <div class="topology-container">
      <canvas id="lcsCanvas" width="820" height="400"></canvas>
    </div>

    <div class="failover-timeline" id="lcsTimeline"></div>
  </section>

  <!-- LCS Explainer -->
  <section class="explain-section">
    <div class="explain-grid">
      <div class="explain-card">
        <h3>⬆️ Level Promotion</h3>
        <p>
          New SSTables land in <strong>L0</strong>. When L0 has enough SSTables, they're merged
          with <em>overlapping SSTables in L1</em>. L1 can hold up to <strong>10 SSTables</strong>
          (each ~160MB). L2 holds 100, L3 holds 1000, etc. Each level is <em>10× the previous</em>.
          Within each level (except L0), <strong>key ranges never overlap</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="explain-card">
        <h3>📈 Trade-offs</h3>
        <p>
          <strong>Pros:</strong> Reads check at most <em>one SSTable per level</em> — bounded
          read amplification. Predictable latency. Less space overhead (only ~10% temporary).
          <strong>Cons:</strong> Higher <em>write amplification</em> — each piece of data may be
          rewritten ~10× as it promotes through levels. Not ideal for write-heavy workloads.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Time-Window Compaction (TWCS) -->
  <section class="flow-section">
    <h2>⏰ Time-Window Compaction (TWCS)</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">Designed for time-series data. SSTables are grouped by time window. Within each window, STCS is used. Once a window closes, its SSTables are frozen.</p>

    <div class="flow-controls">
      <div class="slider-group">
        <label>Speed: <strong id="twcsSpeedLabel">1×</strong></label>
        <input type="range" id="twcsSpeedSlider" min="1" max="5" value="1" class="slot-slider">
      </div>
      <button id="twcsStartBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">▶ Start</button>
      <button id="twcsResetBtn" class="action-btn reset-btn">🔄 Reset</button>
    </div>

    <div class="flow-status" id="twcsStatus">
      <span class="status-badge idle" id="twcsBadge">Ready</span>
      <span class="status-text" id="twcsStatusText">Start the simulation to see time-window compaction</span>
    </div>

    <div class="topology-container">
      <canvas id="twcsCanvas" width="820" height="380"></canvas>
    </div>

    <div class="failover-timeline" id="twcsTimeline"></div>
  </section>

  <!-- TWCS Explainer -->
  <section class="explain-section">
    <div class="explain-card highlight-card">
      <h3>💡 Why Time-Window?</h3>
      <p>
        Time-series data has a natural ordering by time. TWCS groups SSTables into
        <strong>time windows</strong> (e.g., 1 hour). Within the active window, <em>STCS</em>
        is used for compaction. Once a window closes (no more writes expected), SSTables are
        <strong>frozen</strong> — never compacted again. This avoids wasting I/O on old, static data.
        <em>TTL-expired data</em> is efficiently dropped when entire windows expire.
        <strong>Caveat:</strong> works best with <em>time-ordered writes</em> — out-of-order writes
        can land in wrong windows and prevent efficient cleanup.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Comparison & Selection -->
  <section class="flow-section">
    <h2>⚖️ Strategy Comparison</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">Select a workload type to see which compaction strategy is recommended, with metrics comparison.</p>

    <div class="flow-controls">
      <button id="wlWriteBtn" class="action-btn workload-btn" data-workload="write-heavy">📝 Write-Heavy</button>
      <button id="wlReadBtn" class="action-btn workload-btn" data-workload="read-heavy">📖 Read-Heavy</button>
      <button id="wlTimeBtn" class="action-btn workload-btn" data-workload="time-series">⏰ Time-Series</button>
      <button id="wlMixedBtn" class="action-btn workload-btn" data-workload="mixed">🔀 Mixed</button>
    </div>

    <div class="topology-container">
      <canvas id="compareCanvas" width="820" height="420"></canvas>
    </div>

    <div class="recommendation-box" id="recommendationBox"></div>
  </section>

  <!-- Decision Tree -->
  <section class="explain-section">
    <div class="explain-grid">
      <div class="explain-card">
        <h3>🌳 Decision Tree</h3>
        <p>
          <strong>Is your data time-series?</strong> → Use <em>TWCS</em>.<br>
          <strong>Is your workload read-heavy?</strong> → Use <em>LCS</em>.<br>
          <strong>Is your workload write-heavy?</strong> → Use <em>STCS</em>.<br>
          <strong>Mixed workload?</strong> → Start with <em>STCS</em> (default), benchmark, then consider
          <em>LCS</em> if read latency is a problem.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="explain-card">
        <h3>📊 Key Metrics</h3>
        <p>
          <strong>Write Amplification:</strong> How many times data is rewritten. STCS ≈ <em>2-4×</em>,
          LCS ≈ <em>10-30×</em>, TWCS ≈ <em>2-4×</em>.<br>
          <strong>Read Amplification:</strong> SSTables checked per read. STCS ≈ <em>many</em>,
          LCS ≈ <em>1 per level</em>, TWCS ≈ <em>few per window</em>.<br>
          <strong>Space Amplification:</strong> STCS ≈ <em>2×</em>, LCS ≈ <em>1.1×</em>, TWCS ≈ <em>1×</em>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <footer class="viz-footer">
    <p>Based on <a href="https://cassandra.apache.org/doc/latest/cassandra/operating/compaction/" target="_blank">Apache Cassandra Compaction Documentation</a> and <a href="https://www.datastax.com/blog/leveled-compaction-in-apache-cassandra" target="_blank">DataStax Compaction Guides</a></p>
  </footer>

  <div class="share-buttons">
    <span>Share this visualization:</span>
    <a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=Interactive%20visualization%20of%20Cassandra%20compaction%20strategies%20(STCS%2C%20LCS%2C%20TWCS)&url=https://systeminternals.dev/cassandra/compaction/" target="_blank" class="share-btn">𝕏 Twitter</a>
    <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/sharing/share-offsite/?url=https://systeminternals.dev/cassandra/compaction/" target="_blank" class="share-btn">in LinkedIn</a>
    <a href="https://news.ycombinator.com/submitlink?u=https://systeminternals.dev/cassandra/compaction/&t=Interactive%20Cassandra%20Compaction%20Strategies%20Visualizer" target="_blank" class="share-btn">🟧 Hacker News</a>
  </div>
</div>
</BaseLayout>

